A '''Neo-classical contract''' is a form of contract, defined by McNeil, describing a [[contract]] dependent upon [[wikt:trilateral|trilateral]] governance, in which "[[wikt:third party|third party]] assistance" is used  for resolving disputes or evaluating performance.<ref>I.R. Macneil, “Contracts: adjustment of long-term economic relations under classical, neoclassical, and relational contract law” (1977) ''Northwestern University Law Review'' vol:72 pg:854 .</ref> Such contracts form a distinct group, along with classical and relational contracts, in McNeil's system of classification.

